http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/Intense-cold-conditions-prevail-in-parts-of-North/article13979806.ece

Intense cold conditions prevailed in parts of north India on Sunday as the mercury plummeted to minus 15 degrees Celsius in Kargil, while Kashmir Valley braced up for possible snowfall over two days from Monday.Kargil in frontier Ladakh region of Jammu and Kashmir had recorded a minimum of minus 10 degrees Celsius Saturday.A Jammu and Kashmir MeT official said the mercury in nearby Leh, went down by over three degrees, as it recorded a low of minus 12.6 degrees Celsius against the previous night’s minus of 9.2 degrees Celsius.The national capital, however, experienced a relatively warmer day with the minimum temperature settling at 8 degrees Celsius, a degree above the normal for this time of the season.The Valley is currently under the grip of the 40-day harsh winter period known as ‘Chillai-Kalan’ which began on December 21 and during which the chances of snowfall are most frequent and maximum.The cold wave tightened its grip in other places in Kashmir division with Qazigund — the gateway town to the Valley along Srinagar-Jammu National Highway recording the minimum of minus 2.8 degrees Celsius, the official said.There was some respite from the harsh winter in Srinagar where the minimum temperature settled at minus 2.7 degrees Celsius against Saturday’s minus 3.8 degrees Celsius, he said.In other parts of north India, Amritsar recorded the lowest temperature in Punjab at 2.8 degrees Celsius.Narnaul turned out to be the coldest place in Haryana, recording a low of 4.8 degrees Celsius while Hisar also experienced a cold night at 5.8 degrees Celsius.Chandigarh had a cold night with mercury dipping to 5.5 degrees Celsius, the MeT Department report here said.Apart from Amritsar, Ludhiana and Patiala also reeled under biting chill conditions recording below normal minimum at 3.4 degrees Celsius and 5.5 degrees Celsius respectively.Karnal recorded a low of 6 degrees Celsius while Ambala’s low settled at 7.7 degrees Celsius.Mercury again dipped in parts of Rajasthan with Churu being reported the coldest place in the state at a little over 5 degrees Celsius.Meanwhile, due to fog in neighbouring states of Haryana, Punjab, Uttar Pradesh and Delhi, nine trains of North Western Railways were running late, and one train’s time was rescheduled, its CPRO Tarun Jain said.Meanwhile, Jaipur’s minimum temperature also dipped to 9.2, about 0.8 degree less than Saturday’s.Jaisalmer, Barmer, and Jodhpur in western regions were still experiencing higher temperature within the range of 12 to 14.4 degrees Celsius.Mount Abu, sole hill station in Rajasthan, recorded 7.4 degree Celsius. PTI